<DOC><DOCNO> AP880309-0315 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 2108EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     03-09 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Six People Killed by Pro-Sinhalese Group</HEAD><DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A group that opposes a peace accordwith minority Tamils killed six people from the Sinhalese ethnicmajority, including a government official and two family members,military officers said Wednesday.   The officers blamed the outlawed People's Liberation Front, aSinhalese group, for the killings near Beliatta, 85 miles southeastof Colombo.   They said the official, P.K. Dissanayake, and two members of hisfamily were abducted Tuesday night by men wearing police uniformsand their bodies were found early early Wednesday. Three otherSinhalese were shot dead Wednesday, the officers said, speaking oncondition of anonymity.   Authorities blame the Sinhalese group for more than 150 killingssince July 1987 in its campaign against a peace agreement designedto end a 4-year-old Tamil separatist war that has taken more than8,000 lives. The Front claims the July 29 agreement grants Tamilstoo many concessions.   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of SriLanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majoritySinhalese, a predominantly Buddhist ethnic group that controlsgovernment and military.</TEXT></DOC>